'''Alfred Emanuel Sarasin''' (born 13 April 1922 in [[Basel]], † 8 May 2005)<ref name="A">{{cite web |url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D48799.php |title=Sarasin, Alfred E. |author=Hermann Wichers |date=1 June 2012 |publisher=Historisches Lexikon der Schweiz |access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref> was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] banker and politician.
His grandfather was Alfred Sarasin-Iselin. His father was banker, Bernhard Sarasin, who died at an early age in 1950. Alfred E. Sarasin became successor in the management of the bank Sarasin. From 1954 to 2005, he worked well beyond his own business for the [[Banking in Switzerland|Swiss banking]] industry, presided from 1965 to 1986 for the [[Swiss Bankers Association]] and was also President of the Bank Council of the [[Swiss National Bank]]. In 1987, the company [[J. Safra Sarasin|A. Sarasin & Cie]] became a limited partnership with the newly converted name, Bank Sarasin & Cie.<ref name="A" />
After his death, the bank was sold in 2007 by the bankers Erik Sarasin, Andreas Sarasin and Yves Sarasin to the Dutch [[Rabobank]]. Rabobank sold the bank later to the [[Safra Group]] in [[Geneva]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.de/newsticker/bloomberg/article106011835/Jahresgewinn-von-Sarasin-sinkt-20-Kapitalabfluesse-im-2-Hj.html |title=Jahresgewinn von Sarasin sinkt 20% |author=Giles Broom |date=23 February 2012 |publisher=WeltN24 |access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>
